{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621084"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:49:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:49:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.75,0.08,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66226"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51674"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5411"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22156"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66226"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring a public health investigation of a foodborne illness outbreak at a wedding reception, cases began appearing within 6 hours of the event. Most affected individuals developed symptoms between 8-12 hours after the reception, with case numbers rapidly declining thereafter.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the expected appearance of the epidemic curve in this outbreak?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple peaks occurring over several weeks","Bell-shaped curve with a single peak","Biphasic curve with two distinct peaks","Gradual rise with sustained plateau","Irregular pattern with random spikes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebell-shaped curve with a single peak\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of a point source outbreak, such as food contamination at a single event. All exposed individuals encounter the pathogen at approximately the same time, leading to a rapid rise and fall in cases after the incubation period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple peaks occurring over several weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest an outbreak with multiple exposure events or person-to-person spread, which is inconsistent with a single contaminated meal at a wedding reception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egradual rise with sustained plateau\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs when there is an ongoing source of contamination, such as a contaminated water supply, rather than a single exposure event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiphasic curve with two distinct peaks\u003C/strong\u003E represents either secondary transmission or two separate exposure events, neither of which fits the scenario of a single meal at a wedding reception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eirregular pattern with random spikes\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly seen in endemic diseases or when cases are not epidemiologically linked, unlike this clear single-event exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rapid onset and decline of cases within a specific timeframe after the wedding reception is consistent with a point source outbreak, where all cases are exposed simultaneously to a contaminated food item.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An epidemic curve shows the frequency of new cases over time during a disease outbreak.","The shape of an epidemic curve can indicate the type of outbreak source (point source, continuous source, or person-to-person).","Point source outbreaks typically show a rapid rise and fall in cases with a single peak."],"references":["Nsoesie EO, Beckman R, Marathe M, Lewis B. Prediction of an Epidemic Curve: A Supervised Classification Approach. Stat Commun Infect Dis. 2011 Jan 1;3(1):5. doi: 10.2202/1948-4690.1038. Epub 2011 Oct 4. PMID: 22997545; PMCID: PMC3445421.","Singh H, Srivastava HM, Baleanu D. Methods of Mathematical Modeling, Academic Press, 2022. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-323-99888-8.00008-5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51674"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51674"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T15:04:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T21:26:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9357"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66226"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam